excerpt: Elaborate madrasa founded in AD 1351--56 & known for its  historic Marinid & Moroccan architecture.
detail_description: Bou Inania Madrasa, founded in the mid-14th century by Marinid ruler Abu Inan Faris, is a stunning example of historic Marinid and Moroccan architecture. Located near Bab Boujeloud, it is considered one of the most beautiful residential colleges of Kairaouine University.
name: Bou Inania Madrasa

excerpt: 14th-century school for Islamic studies featuring ornate tile work & dramatic architecture.
detail_description: Al Attarine Madrasa is a 14th-century Islamic school located near the bustling Souk al-Attarine in Fes. Built by the Marinid sultan Uthman II Abu Said, it features stunning tile work, intricate zellije tilework, ornate carved stucco, and delicate cedar woodwork throughout its galleried courtyard.
name: Al Attarine Madrasa

excerpt: This museum in a former palace has displays of traditional arts, including pottery & wood carving.
detail_description: Dar Batha Museum, located in a former palace, showcases traditional arts and crafts such as pottery, wood carving, jewelry, embroidery, carpets, copperware, and wrought iron. The museum's centerpiece exhibit is the ceramics room featuring the renowned Fes blue ceramics colored with cobalt. The original palace decoration and the beautiful internal courtyard garden filled with shady trees and tall palms create a serene oasis within the city.
name: Dar Batha Museum of Islamic Arts
address: Oued Fejjaline, 5 Ave du Batha, Fes, Morocco

detail_description: The Mosque and University Kairaouine, founded in AD 857 by Fatima, is a significant landmark in the Western Muslim world. It was once the largest mosque in Morocco and housed the West's first university. The Kairaouine University is one of the oldest continuously operating educational institutions globally. Located in Fes el Bali, this area exudes cultural and spiritual richness with its vibrant souks offering artisan products.
name: Mosque and University of al-Qarawiyyin

excerpt: Fes El Bali is an ancient walled medina with narrow, car-free streets and ornamented entryways like Bab Guissa and the Blue Gate. Vast 9th-century Karaouiyne University is tiled in vivid painted ceramics, while the towering R’cif Mosque overlooks a lively market square. Souk vendors specialize in perfumes, spices, lamps, and leather, and dining choices range from street kebabs to stylish gourmet restaurants.
detail_description: Fes El Bali is an ancient walled medina with narrow, car-free streets and ornate entryways such as Bab Guissa and the Blue Gate. The 9th-century Karaouiyne University is adorned with vibrant painted ceramics, while the towering R’cif Mosque overlooks a bustling market square. The souks offer a variety of goods including perfumes, spices, lamps, leather items, and dining options ranging from street kebabs to upscale gourmet restaurants.
name: Fes El Bali

excerpt: Former inn, now a 3-story museum featuring intricate wood carvings & various art pieces & crafts.
detail_description: The Nejjarine Museum of Wooden Arts & Crafts is a 3-story museum housed in an 18th-century funduq, once a resting place for merchants. The building has been meticulously restored and now showcases traditional woodwork from across Morocco. Located on Nejjarine Square, the museum features intricate wood carvings, various art pieces, and crafts. Visitors can also enjoy mint tea at the museum's cafe while taking in the authentic atmosphere of this historical site.
name: Nejjarine Museum of Wooden Arts & Crafts

excerpt: Royal palace, popular for photos in front of a colorful, imposing facade & gold-colored doors.
detail_description: The Royal Palace in Fez, also known as Dar el Makhzen, is a must-see landmark with its colorful mosaic architecture, landscaped gardens, and impressive golden doors adorned with handcrafted brass knockers. Although visitors cannot explore the palace grounds, they can admire it from one of the seven remarkable gates featuring Moroccan tiles and carved cedarwood. The largest royal palace in Morocco, it serves as the official residence of the King when he visits the city.
name: The Royal Palace of Fez

detail_description: Bab Boujeloud is a great starting point to explore the old medina of Fes. From there, you can wander down Talaa Kebira and visit the Medersa Bou Inania, which is open to non-Muslims. Nearby, you'll find the spice-scented Souk el Attarine and the impressive Kairaouine Mosque.
name: Bab Boujeloud

excerpt: Museum in an old fort showing weapons & armor from different eras, plus scenic views from the roof.
detail_description: Borj Nord Museum, located in Fes, Morocco, is a historic fortress turned museum that offers visitors a glimpse into its past as a tightly secured defensive structure and battle fort. Constructed in 1582 under the Saadian Sultan Ahmed El Mansour Eddahbi, the fortress now houses an impressive collection of over 5,000 weapons and military artifacts. The museum provides scenic views from its roof and showcases European-styled changes to the architecture.
name: Borj Nord Museum

excerpt: The Mellah of Fez is the historic Jewish quarter of Fez, Morocco. It is located in Fes el-Jdid, the part of Fez which contains the Royal Palace, and is believed to date from the mid-15th century. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Mellah, a historic Jewish quarter in Fez, Morocco, is renowned for its intricate balconies and wrought-iron windows. Established in the 15th century after Jews were relocated from the medina, it served as royal financial consultants and intermediaries between rulers and citizens. Despite facing repression until the French protectorate in 1912, Mellah's Jewish community thrived.
name: Mellah

excerpt: Hilltop ruins of 2 tall mausoleums with horseshoe-shaped entrances built in the 14th century.
detail_description: The Marinid Tombs, built in the 14th century, are a collection of impressive mausoleums and graves located on a hill overlooking the city of Fes. The goldstone tombs capture the opulence and beauty of this historical site. While little remains of the original decoration, visitors can still wander through the horseshoe arches and stucco walls to experience a sense of mystery.
name: Marinid Tombs

excerpt: Created in the 19th century, this park offers ponds & lush green areas with 3,000 species of plants.
detail_description: Jnan Sbil, also known as Bou Jeloud Gardens, is a historic park located between Fes el-Jdid and Fes el-Bali. Established in the 18th century by Sultan Moulay Abdallah, this lush green space features ponds and over 3,000 species of plants. After falling into decline, the park was revitalized in the 2000s and now boasts meticulously tended water gardens with geometric fountains adorned with zellige tiles.
name: Jnan Sbil

excerpt: Fes is a northeastern Moroccan city often referred to as the country’s cultural capital. It’s primarily known for its Fes El Bali walled medina, with medieval Marinid architecture, vibrant souks and old-world atmosphere. The medina is home to religious schools such as the 14th-century Bou Inania and Al Attarine, both decorated with elaborate cedar carvings and ornate tile work.
detail_description: Fes, a city in northeastern Morocco, is often hailed as the country's cultural capital. Its Fes El Bali walled medina showcases medieval Marinid architecture and bustling souks, exuding an old-world charm. The medina also houses religious schools like the Bou Inania and Al Attarine, adorned with intricate cedar carvings and ornate tile work.
name: Fes

excerpt: Tannery & leather trader treating & selling locally-crafted goods with a terrace for dyeing.
detail_description: Chouara Tannery is a must-see in Fes, with its ancient dyeing vats displaying vibrant reds, yellows, and blues. Although the smell of animal skins can be overpowering, the terrace offers a breathtaking view of the colorful vats. Nearby stores on Rue Chouara showcase an array of leather goods like coats, bags, and traditional slippers.
name: Fez Tannery Tour and Shopping

detail_description: Bab Boujloud, also known as the Blue Gate, serves as the main entrance to the heart of the Medina. It is a popular spot for taking pictures, especially at night when it is illuminated. The area around this gate is lined with eateries offering inexpensive Moroccan dishes such as brochettes, tagine, and couscous. While some may lack in hygiene standards, they are favored for their affordability and people-watching opportunities.
name: Bab Boujloud

excerpt: Built in the 17th century, this simple Orthodox Jewish synagogue was built by Mimoun Ben Sidan.
detail_description: The Aben Danan Synagogue, also known as the Ibn Danan Synagogue, is a historic Orthodox Jewish synagogue in Fes El Jadid El Mallah, Morocco. Constructed in the 17th century by Mimoun Ben Sidan to accommodate over 1500 Jewish families expelled from Spain, it stands as one of the oldest synagogues in the region.
name: Aben Danan Synagogue

detail_description: In the heart of Fez's medina lies the Henna Souk, a vibrant marketplace where centuries-old traditions of bargaining and craftsmanship still thrive. This bustling area is home to a variety of small souks run by guilds, offering an array of goods such as leather items, woodwork, metal crafts, henna products, and even equestrian accessories.
name: Henna Souk and pottery

detail_description: Cafe Clock, located in the heart of the medina, is a renowned crosscultural cafe in Fez. It offers a diverse menu featuring Moroccan and international cuisine, including the popular camel burger and vegetarian options. The cafe also hosts cultural workshops where visitors can learn about Moroccan cooking, Arabic language, calligraphy, storytelling, music (oud), and even get henna tattoos.
name: Cafe Clock
address: 7 Derb el Magana, 252 Rue Talaa Kebira, Fes, Morocco

detail_description: The Mausoleum of Moulay Idriss II is a significant spiritual site in Fez, Morocco. Founded by the Moroccan ruler saint Moulay Idris II in CE 808, it served as the capital of Morocco during his reign. The mausoleum's unique architecture and tranquil ambiance make it an over 1200-year-old sacred place accessible exclusively to Muslims.
name: Mausoleum of Moulay Idriss II
address: 7 souk Sebbat kissariat El Kifah, Fes, Morocco

detail_description: Ville Nouvelle, also known as Hamrya in Meknes, was developed under the direction of Marechal Louis Hubert Lyautey to modernize major cities. In Fez, it is situated on the outskirts beyond el Jdid and the Mellah. The area features the popular Borj Fez mall with a large Carrefour supermarket offering wine and liquor.
name: Ville Nouvelle

detail_description: Médina de Fès is a captivating walled city in Northern Africa that offers a medieval experience with its maze of alleys, doors, and handicraft workshops. Navigating the labyrinthine streets can be challenging for first-timers, making a guide highly recommended due to the unreliable GPS and the hilly terrain. The bustling marketplace showcases an array of goods carried by donkey or mule trains, but visitors should be cautious as some vendors may overcharge.
name: Médina de Fès

detail_description: Less renowned than other attractions, Blue Gate is still a stunning sight to behold.
name: Blue Gate

detail_description: Place Seffarine is a charming square nestled in the heart of Fez el-Bali's medina, flanked by the souk of dyers and tanners. The square is named after the coppersmiths who historically practiced their craft here, creating an array of utensils such as teapots, trays, pots, and more. While today's artisans mainly focus on repairing old vessels, visitors can still observe them skillfully shaping metal with rhythmic hammering.
name: Place Seffarine

detail_description: Fes El Jdid, also known as New Fes, was established in 1276 to serve as a royal capital and house the court. This walled city is home to numerous mosques and medersas that were built during a period of flourishing trade. The area is characterized by its bustling souks where visitors can find an array of goods such as Berber rugs, leather items, kaftans, djellabas, and traditional Moroccan slippers.
name: Fes El Jdid

detail_description: The Ruined Garden, owned by Robert Johnstone, is a lush oasis in Fes. The restaurant offers a charming dining experience in the ruins of an old riad surrounded by vibrant flowers. Known for its authentic Fassi cuisine, the menu features traditional dishes like slow-roasted lamb mechoui and saffron chicken alongside reimagined street food.
name: The Ruined Garden
address: 15 Derb Idrissy Sidi Ahmed Chaoui Medina 30110, Siaj, Fes, Morocco

detail_description: The Cherratine Medersa is a must-visit in Fez, Morocco. This ancient Koranic school features three floors with over 100 small rooms where students once studied the Quran. The central atrium leads to the upper floors, showcasing its complex and articulated structure. For a local and Muslim experience, visitors can explore the building for a fee of 20 dirhams. It offers great opportunities for photographers to get creative and learn about Islamic teachings in a modernized setting.
name: Cherratine Medersa

detail_description: Andalusian Mosque, located in the heart of the Medina, is a historic site dating back to the 9th century. The mosque features grand carved doors at its north entrance and a domed Zenet minaret. Built by Andalusian refugees from Cordoba, it stands as one of the oldest mosques in the world. The intricate cedarwood carvings in the eaves showcase typical Andalusian architecture and reflect Moroccan craftsmanship.
name: Andalusian Mosque

detail_description: Rainbow Street Art in Fes Medina is a vibrant and colorful alley filled with beautiful artwork and paintings. It's easily located by searching for it on Google Maps. The street is adorned with rainbow colors that catch the eye, showcasing a variety of art pieces and wares, including charming woodcraft sold by a friendly old man. To fully appreciate the beauty without crowds, it's recommended to visit at night.
name: Rainbow Street Art

detail_description: Nestled across from the Bou Inania Madrasa on Talaa Kebira Street, Dar al-Magana, or the "clockhouse," is a remarkable historical site that showcases an ancient water clock. This fascinating creation dates back to the late 13th century and was designed by Abou '-Hassan Ali, a notable figure in trigonometry and astronomy. Although it underwent removal for research purposes, restoration efforts have revitalized its intricate woodwork while awaiting updates to its metal components.
name: Dar al-Magana (Water Clock)
address: Rue Rue Talaa Kebira, Fes, Morocco

detail_description: Cafe Volubilis is located in the ancient Roman city of Volubilis, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in Morocco. The cafe offers a unique experience with its backdrop of towering Roman columns, showcasing the diverse historical and geopolitical roots of the country. It's a great spot for people-watching while enjoying affordable yet quality coffee on the sidewalk.
name: Cafe Volubilis

excerpt: Ornate Moorish-style quarters in a lavish hotel with fine dining, a rooftop terrace & a plush spa.
detail_description: Riad Fes - Relais & Châteaux is a luxurious hotel located in the heart of the ancient city of Fes. It perfectly combines refinement and inspiration, offering guests a serene atmosphere with a decor reminiscent of Arabian Nights. The hotel's Moorish-style architecture and lavish interiors provide an opulent setting for travelers to indulge in fine dining, relax on the rooftop terrace, and pamper themselves at the plush spa.
name: Riad Fes - Relais & Châteaux

detail_description: Embark on a scenic adventure by hiking the trail to Jbel Zalagh, the largest mountain overlooking Fez. The two-hour hike offers stunning views of the city and takes you through olive groves and wild lavender, providing a peaceful escape from the bustling streets below. Keep in mind that the weather can be hot and dry, so it's essential to bring plenty of water. The trail is easily accessible from the city, making it a wonderful day hike for nature enthusiasts.
name: Trail to Hike Jbel (Mount) Zalagh

excerpt: Ancient military tower whose exterior is open to the public with expansive city views.
detail_description: Borj Sud is an ancient military tower located in southern Fez, offering a glimpse into the city's historical defenses. Built during the 16th century, it stands as a significant landmark just outside the medina. Unlike its sister fort, Borj Nord, it retains a simple square shape without corner bastions. Visitors can easily reach it from Bab Jdid and enjoy panoramic views of Fez from its terrace.
name: Borj Sud

detail_description: Fondouk Bazaar is a trendy and modern restaurant located in Fes, offering a fusion of Mediterranean, Middle Eastern, and Moroccan cuisine. The restaurant features beautiful decor with an open-air courtyard adorned with colorful lanterns. The menu showcases an imaginative take on local flavors, focusing on healthy ingredients while delivering rich taste. Despite being situated in the Medina, it stands out as a busy and artsy hideaway popular for its diverse culinary offerings.
name: Fondouk Bazaar

detail_description: Tanneries de Fes is a must-visit attraction in the northeast corner of Fes el Bali, near the Qaraouiyine Mosque. It's a hub of Morocco's leather industry since medieval times. Visitors can witness the traditional leather-making process and explore different stages of production. The tannery offers an exclusive ballet performance for tourists and provides an opportunity to learn about this ancient art form that has remained unchanged over time.
name: Tanneries de Fes

detail_description: Cimitero ebraico, located in the mellah (Jewish quarter) of Fez, is a serene and architecturally impressive site. The Rue des Merinides, with its distinctive wooden houses, leads to this cemetery where white tombs cascade down the hill. Some of these tombs are dedicated to rabbis, including the tomb of Rabbi Vidal Hasserfaty from 1600.
name: Jewish Cemetery of Fes

detail_description: Riad Moulay Driss & Giacomo in Fes is a unique luxury riad with striking red and orange tones, stained glass, and a stunning courtyard. It's run by a family who used to live in the building before converting it into a riad. The hosts are known for their warm hospitality and attention to detail, making guests feel at home. Visitors praise the tasteful Moroccan decor and the delicious homemade meals served at the riad.
name: Riad Moulay Driss & GIACOMO FES

detail_description: New Relax offers a variety of options for relaxation and pampering. Visitors can enjoy the local experience by visiting public hammams or bathhouses, while those seeking a more private and luxurious experience can indulge in the services offered at private hammams such as Spa Laaroussa. Additionally, visitors can also find tranquil spots to enjoy coffee and free Wi-Fi, making it an ideal destination for both relaxation and leisurely activities.
name: New Relax

detail_description: El Glaoui Palace, a remarkable gem nestled within the medina of Fes, invites visitors to step back in time and experience its rich history. Once the residence of Thami El Glaoui, this stunning palace served as a seat of power and showcases exquisite architectural details like intricate stucco work and beautifully carved cedarwood doors.
name: El Glaoui Palace

detail_description: Hammam Mernissi & Spa, located in the heart of Fez's old medina, offers a traditional Moroccan spa experience. The renovated public hammam features a private section where men and women can relax together amidst traditional decor including patterned tiles, marble, and candle lamps. Upon arrival, guests are greeted with Moroccan mint tea before indulging in a steamy hammam session followed by an invigorating full-body scrub and massage.
name: Hammam Mernissi & Spa
address: N°46 Serrajin Bab Boujloud 30120, Old, Fes, Morocco

detail_description: Made in M is a charming bistro located in the Medina, offering a bohemian-style interior and traditional Moroccan cuisine with a modern twist. The small family-owned restaurant serves popular dishes like Khlii, eggplant, mozzarella, tomato batbout, and horn gazelle pastry. It's an ideal spot to relax and enjoy fresh mint tea or Moroccan tagines while surrounded by straw chandeliers and large pillows.
name: Made in M

excerpt: 80-hectare royal palace complex, not open to the public, with an elaborate brass, wood & tile gate.
detail_description: Palais Royal Dar El Makhzen is an expansive royal palace complex spanning 80 hectares, located in Fes el-Jdid. While not accessible to the public, its elaborate brass, wood, and tile gate make for a stunning photo opportunity. Dating back to the 13th century, this architectural marvel showcases intricate Moroccan design patterns on its seven bronze doors. Although the royal family does not reside here, it remains a significant site for their visits.
name: Palais Royal Dar El Makhzen

detail_description: Chez Rachid is a highly recommended restaurant located near the popular Bab Boujloud Gate, The Blue Gate in Fes. It offers incredible food at great prices and has received high praise from both locals and tourists. The restaurant provides a warm and welcoming atmosphere with friendly staff. Additionally, it is known for its delicious Moroccan cuisine, including beef tagine and chicken skewers. For those seeking a more Western dining experience, Cafe Clock is also nearby and offers fusion-style dishes with beautiful terrace views.
name: Chez Rachid

detail_description: Sahrij Madrasa is a historic Islamic school situated in Fez, Morocco, near the Andalusian Mosque. Commissioned by the Marinid Sultan Abu al-Hassan in 1321, it features a stunning courtyard with an ornate ablution pool known as "sahrij." The architecture boasts carved cedar, sculpted marble, vibrant zellige tiles, and stucco that evoke the splendor of Granada's Alhambra palace complex.
name: Sahrij Madrasa

detail_description: Maze of Fez is a renowned destination in Fes for those seeking high-quality modern and classic Moroccan rugs. The selection is fantastic, and the team, led by Brahim and Idris, offers excellent service. Customers can negotiate prices and even place special orders for custom designs. Visitors appreciate the low-pressure environment and the opportunity to learn about the intricate process behind these beautiful carpets.
name: Maze of fez Moroccan Rugs

detail_description: Bab Chorfa is a gate in the old city of Fez. It is less colorful than the Blue Gate, but it is more impressive. The markets area near Bab Chorfa is not as exciting as other spots in the Medina, but it may be loved by locals.
name: Bab Chorfa

excerpt: Bustling place with a market featuring produce, meats, spices & an array of street-food stalls.
detail_description: Rue Talaa Kebira is a vibrant and lively street known for its bustling market offering a wide variety of produce, meats, spices, and street food stalls. This narrow street runs across the city from east to west and is famous for its diverse shopping options and delectable street food. As you stroll along this bustling thoroughfare, you'll be captivated by the array of fabrics including silks, satin, and leather on display.
name: Rue Talaa Kebira
